observations.recommendation:
We recommended that:

Management prepare and submit the Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System;



The Municipal Engineer provide the Municipal Accountant with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;

The LGU shall maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map and shall keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components; and

The Municipal Accountant prepare the Journal Voucher to record the inventory of the local road network and its components in the general ledger and the Local Road Network Ledger Card; keep and maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network.

We recommended that:

The Municipal Accountant prepare the necessary adjusting journal entries for bank reconciling items which understates various cash accounts, exert efforts to identify those undetermined reconciling items/differences and ensure that the bank reconciliation statements are duly supported upon submission to the Office of the Auditor;

Henceforth, strictly adhere to the provisions of Par. 27 of International Public Sector Accounting Standards (IPSAS) 1 and Items 3.1 to 3.4 of COA Circular No. 96-011.

We recommended that Management:

Fully liquidate all cash advances at year-end through the submission of a liquidation report or refund of the remaining balances as prescribed under COA Circular 97-002 to avoid the accumulation of cash advances and risk of loss thru theft and or misapplication of funds;

Require the liquidation of long outstanding cash advances from the Accountable Officers or withhold their salaries as prescribed under the above-cited Circular;

Instruct the Accountable Officers and Accounting Department to reconcile their records and close those advances already liquidated but not yet reflected in the books; and

Verify the details of the undetermined amount of P173,760.00 for possible issuance of demand letters for the liquidation of the related cash advances.

We recommended that Management:

Expedite the transfer of title of the lots where the New Municipal Hall is located in the name of the LGU to protect the properties from the risk of disputes or claims by other parties;

Direct the Accounting Office to record in the books the lot in Luttuad, Diffun and the lot of the Evacuation Center in Rizal Diffun, with due consideration of the measurement prescribed in IPSAS 17;

Initiate strategies to verify the details of the amount recorded in 2019 and prior years to present reliable financial statements; and

Direct the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to ensure that the Municipality has absolute or legal ownership over the properties before implementing the construction of buildings and other improvements on lands.

We recommended that:

Management strictly adhere to the provisions of the New Government Accounting System for LGUs regarding the procedures of accounting for and managing supplies;

Accordingly, procured supplies and materials must be recorded as inventories upon purchase and the corresponding expense accounts must be taken up only upon issuance/s thereof.

We recommended that Management:

We recommended that Management enumerate specifically the Priority Infrastructure Projects in its Annual Budget to facilitate the evaluation of the projects charged against the 20% Development Fund;

Strict adherence to the provisions DBM-DOF-DILG Joint Memorandum Circular No. 1 dated November 4, 2020 is enjoined.

We recommended that:

Management to direct the Treasurer’s Office personnel to conduct intensive tax campaign and employ collection strategies, giving priority to the collection of the Real Property Tax and Special Education Tax Receivables which had accumulated to ₱38.103 million and prevent the balance of the accounts from accumulating further;

We also recommended that Notice of Delinquency or final demand letters be sent to the delinquent owners and avail remedies through levy on real property or judicial actions provided under RA 7160.

We recommended that Management:

Ensure to enter into Contract of Lease/MOAs to all occupants of the stalls in the market;

Strictly impose the provisions in the contract regarding non-payment of rentals by the lease owners and institute measures to collect the arrears.

We recommended that Management: 

Strictly comply with COA Circular No. 77-61 which provides the Manual on Audit for Fuel Consumption of Government Motor Vehicles and submit Monthly Report of Official Travels and Monthly Report of Fuel Consumptions to ascertain the reasonableness of the gasoline consumed;

Otherwise, withhold the salaries of the responsible persons if warranted.

We recommended that Management:

Exert all efforts to verify the details of the account and reconcile with the Audit Team;

Exhaust all available remedies in enforcing the immediate settlement of all audit disallowances pursuant to pertinent provisions of COA Circular No. 2009-006 and to be more prudent in the processing of claims for payments to avoid audit disallowances and suspensions.

We recommended that Management:
Issue final demand letters and impose the necessary and applicable remedies or penalties to those who will not adhere to the demand letters such as withholding of their salaries or any claims due them, if necessary and warranted;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to review the recorded Due from Officers and Employees and draw reclassification or adjusting entries, if necessary;
Strictly implement the established guideline that no cash advances will be granted unless the previous cash advance given to him is first settled or a proper accounting thereof is made, that a certification of no outstanding cash advances for all cash advance requests has to be attached to the disbursement voucher, in order to prevent the accumulation of unliquidated cash advances; and
Stop the practice of granting cash advances for expenses other than TEVs to elected officials or employees unless they are designated as disbursing officers and properly bonded.

We recommended that Management:
Discontinue the use of the 20% Development Fund for administrative expenses, including the repair of administrative offices;
Review and, if feasible, reallocate the amount that was used for administrative programs to eligible development projects that benefit the community and promote efficient local governance;
Submit a formal report detailing the corrective actions taken to address this noncompliance, as well as measures to prevent future misallocations; and
Ensure that all future expenditures charged under the 20% DF strictly conform to the criteria set forth in the DBM-DOF-DILG Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2020-1.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
Facilitate the tracing and locating of relevant documents to serve as basis in adjusting identified reconciling items in the respective reciprocal accounts;
Prepare a reconciliation report of reciprocal accounts and take up the necessary adjustments in the books of accounts to ensure that all reconciling items are resolved and/or adjusted on a timely basis;
Prepare the necessary adjusting entries to bring the correct balances of the accounts; and
Perform constant review and appraisal of transactions to deter errors and omissions and include disclosure in the Notes to FS for fair presentation of Financial Statements.

In view of the above audit observations, we recommended that Management:
Implement strictly the provision of the guidelines above that no additional cash advances must be granted unless the previous cash advances are settled first, in order to stop the accumulation of the unliquidated cash advances;
Stop the granting of cash advances without legally specific purposes;
Always require the clearance from financial obligations for officials or employees separating from the service, through resignation or retirement, to ensure that their cash advances are settled, either by submission of documents or through payment by deduction from whatever claim due them; and
Continuously require and issue demand letters to the accountable officers with unliquidated cash advances and impose the necessary and applicable remedies or penalties to those who will not adhere to the demand letter, such as withholding of their salaries or any claims due them, if necessary.

We recommended the following:
Require the Supply Officer to maintain stock cards which is up-to-date for each inventory item and the Accounting Office for the supplies ledger cards;
Direct the Inventory Committee to conduct the semestral, physical count of inventory items by type, and prepare the Report of Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI). Thereafter, submit a copy to the Auditor, pursuant to Section 124 of the MNGAS for LGUs;
Instruct the General Services Office to consolidate weekly the Requisition Issue Slip using the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued. Based on the SSMI, a JEV shall be prepared by the Municipal Accountant pursuant to Section 121 of the MNGAS for LGUs; and
Prepare the necessary adjustment to reflect the actual correct balances thereof. Likewise, both records of the Municipal Accountant’s Office and General Services Office should be adjusted accordingly in order to present fairly the balances of the inventories in the Financial Statements.

We recommended that Management:
Locate the pertinent documents and establish the correctness and accuracy of the long outstanding balances, and issue demand letters requiring the return of the unrecouped advances;
Assess the collectibility and if proven to be uncollectible and worthless, request for authority to write-off of the dormant accounts in accordance with COA Circular No. 2023-008 dated August 17, 2023;
Coordinate with the contractors and deduct the amount due to them from any unpaid claims from other projects undertaken by the same contractors; and
Initiate legal action to those who refuse to refund the unrecouped advances and impose administrative sanctions against erring agency personnel who failed to recoup the advances from the progress billings and/or surety bond of the contractors concerned, as warranted.

We recommended the following to the Management:
Prepare and submit the Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System;
Direct the OIC-Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;
Maintain a complete Local Road Inventory, Road Map and Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components; and
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare the Journal Voucher to record the inventory of the local road network and its components in the general ledger and the Local Road Network Ledger Card; keep and maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network.

We recommended the Management:
to fully liquidate all cash advances at year-end through the submission of a liquidation report or refund of the remaining balances to avoid risk of loss or misappropriation of funds;
to require the liquidation of long outstanding cash advances from the Accountable Officers or withhold their salaries as prescribed under the above-cited Circular;
adhere strictly to the pertinent provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997 regarding the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances; and
verify the details of the undetermined amount for possible issuance of demand letters for the liquidation of the related cash advances.

We recommend Management to reinforce the strengths of this noble program, and to promote equity, transparency, and accountability, it is recommended that the Municipality of Diffun move forward with enacting a comprehensive policy, preferably via ordinance or resolution. This policy could include:
clearly defined eligibility rules for individuals and organizations;
specific categories of assistance with corresponding funding ceilings;
standard document requirements for application, approval, and liquidation;
a formal evaluation and approval process, with built-in monitoring protocols; and
impact tracking mechanisms to ensure fair access across all sectors.

We recommended that Management:
reinstate the derecognized amounts and strictly adhere to the procedures outlined in COA Circular No. 2020-006 for the derecognition or removal of LGU properties from their books of accounts;
conduct an actual physical count of all biological assets and submit the corresponding inventory report to the audit team to ensure proper documentation and accountability;
reconcile the balances between the Accounting and GSO reports and prepare the necessary adjusting entries to correct any discrepancies; and
direct the Accounting Office and GSO to strictly comply with the prescribed forms for Ledger Cards and Property Cards as outlined in the Manual on the New Government Accounting System for LGUs.

